    <text>
        <body>
            <head>8. Memorandum From the Executive Secretary of the Department of State (<persName
                    corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">Tarnoff</persName>) to the President’s Assistant for
                National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu"
                    >Brzezinski</persName>)<note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d8fn1"
                    >Source: Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material,
                    Brzezinski Office File, Country Chron File, Box 7, Chad. Confidential.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1977-05-27"
                        >May 27, 1977</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="recNT9uoUfRQLT224">Toura Gaba</persName>’s
                    Letter Concerning <rs type="topic" corresp="reczbK4SIoOvxRAff">Food Aid</rs> Air
                    Transport and <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recg32kGM5zOIq0bu">Chadian
                        Relations</rs> with <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>Chadian Ambassador <persName corresp="recNT9uoUfRQLT224">Toura Gaba</persName>’s
                letter to you of May 16<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d8fn2">Not found.</note>
                emphasized two major concerns of his government. He requested one or two aircraft
                and crew to distribute donated foodstuffs to the <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recGxSKiAmmOVqBc0">drought</rs> areas of <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> before the rainy season. He
                requested some form of <rs type="topic" corresp="recfsYEHWUfhmWQY2">security
                    assistance</rs> to help <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>
                cope with <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libyan</placeName> “expansionist
                designs.”</p>
            <p>
                <hi rendition="simple_italic">The Chadian <rs type="topic"
                        corresp="recGxSKiAmmOVqBc0">Drought</rs>
                </hi>
            </p>
            <p>International donors have agreed to contribute 32,400 tons of food to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> because of this year’s recurrence
                of a severe <rs type="topic" corresp="recGxSKiAmmOVqBc0">drought</rs> in that
                nation, over half of which comes from <gloss target="#t_US_1">
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">US</placeName>
                </gloss> sources. Of the total aid, less than 5,000 tons have arrived in <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>. A small <placeName
                    corresp="recUe17pTh04JBoo9">German</placeName>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recu0jAoErrAESV42">airlift</rs> is already underway as an
                interim measure to supply eastern <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn"
                    >Chad</placeName> until food arrives by truck. The <placeName
                    corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">French</placeName> are prepared to mount a limited
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recu0jAoErrAESV42">airlift</rs> to the northern area
                of <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>.</p>
            <p>The Government of <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> has made
                several requests over the past six months to us for a food relief <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recu0jAoErrAESV42">airlift</rs>. Given the inordinately high cost of
                previous food airlifts in 1973 and 1974, we have resisted the Chadian approaches. We
                have told the Chadians that we would only consider an <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recu0jAoErrAESV42">airlift</rs> as a way to move <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="reczbK4SIoOvxRAff">food aid</rs> after all methods of moving food by
                conventional transport had been exhausted, or were ineffective. Poor planning by the
                Government of <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> and the fast
                approaching rainy season may, however, force us to give serious consideration next
                month to an <rs type="topic" corresp="recu0jAoErrAESV42">airlift</rs> or to funding
                expanded airlifts by other donor nations. Chadian President <persName
                    corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh">Malloum</persName> recently told our Ambassador he
                could not understand why “a great country like the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>” could not meet his request for
                planes to distribute food relief. <persName corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh"
                    >Malloum</persName> recalls that the politics of famine played a role in the
                downfall of his predecessor, <persName corresp="rec1jghlzYMRjay4N"
                    >Tombalbaye</persName>.</p>
            <pb facs="0037" n="16" xml:id="pg_16"/>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">
                <rs type="compound-subject" corresp="recg32kGM5zOIq0bu">Chadian Relations</rs> with
                    <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>In a May 21 meeting with our Ambassador, President <persName
                    corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh">Malloum</persName> made a strong plea for <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">U.S.</placeName>
                <rs type="topic" corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB">military assistance</rs>.<note n="3"
                    place="foot" xml:id="d8fn3">In telegram 1697 from Ndjamena, May 21, <persName
                        corresp="reckhTnBrMfatcsTW">Bradford</persName> summarized his meeting with
                        <persName corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh">Malloum</persName>. (National
                    Archives, RG 59, Central Foreign Policy File, D770181–1319)</note> President
                    <persName corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh">Malloum</persName> is deeply concerned by
                rebel activity in northern and eastern <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn"
                    >Chad</placeName>. In the east, the Chadian army has tried to confront the rebel
                forces led by Hissene Habre. The most recent operation, in which the Chadians used
                for the first time <placeName corresp="rec7g4kEoiXWBjoX3">Soviet</placeName>
                equipment acquired in the wake of our refusal to supply <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> with heavy equipment in 1975 proved
                a dismal failure. <persName corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh">Malloum</persName> is also
                very upset by the fact that <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>
                has occupied a sizeable strip of territory in northern <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>, and has long supported rebel
                forces against the Chadian Government. Our Ambassador replied to President <persName
                    corresp="recrjkPIMtguCJpSh">Malloum</persName> by outlining the <rs type="event"
                    corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">Administration</rs>’s new arms policy, and
                suggesting that further discussion be deferred until after you had an opportunity to
                consider Ambassador <persName corresp="recNT9uoUfRQLT224">Toura Gaba</persName>’s
                letter.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Recommendation:</p>
            <p>That you send the attached letter to Ambassador <persName corresp="recNT9uoUfRQLT224"
                    >Toura Gaba</persName>.<note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d8fn4">Not
                    attached.</note>
            </p>
            <closer>
                <signed>
                    <persName corresp="recy5FCK6nhenuQqq">
                        <hi rendition="simple_bold">Peter Tarnoff</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Executive Secretary</hi>
                </signed>
            </closer>
        </body>
    </text>
